    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So basically it's just a lack of oxygen triggering that switch? And when you say the body \"clears it out,\" is that happening immediately inside the muscle cells, or does the lactic acid have to travel somewhere else in the body to be processed?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've hit the nail on the head! The lack of oxygen is indeed the trigger for that switch. When your muscles are working so hard that they can't get enough oxygen, they switch to anaerobic respiration, which produces lactic acid as a byproduct. This is like a backup plan when the main road (aerobic respiration) is too crowded.\n\nNow, about the clearing out process, it's not just happening inside the muscle cells. The lactic acid produced in the muscles doesn't just stay there; it enters the bloodstream and travels to the liver. The liver acts like a recycling center, breaking down the lactic acid into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy or converted back into glucose. This process helps to clear the lactic acid from your muscles and restore them to their pre-workout state. So, while the burning sensation might be a bit of a nuisance, it's just your body's way of telling you that it's working hard and that you need to give it a rest. Just remember, even the most seasoned of warriors need their downtime to recover and come back stronger. So, take it easy on the",
      "source": "target",
